  "issues": [
    {
      "number": 1,
      "id": "I_kwDOSJnFe88AAAABHNBtNA",
      "title": "Underspecified context parameter of Ed25519ph",
      "url": "https://github.com/cose-wg/draft-ietf-cose-split-signing-algs/issues/1",
      "state": "CLOSED",
      "author": "emlun",
      "authorAssociation": "COLLABORATOR",
      "assignees": [],
      "labels": [],
      "body": "The Ed25519ph and Ed25519ctx ciphersuites [[RFC8032][]] have a free `context` parameter, unlike Ed25519 which defines this parameter to take a constant empty argument. We need to define how `context` is handled for Ed25519ph.\n\n[RFC8032]: https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc8032/#section-5.1\n",
      "createdAt": "2026-06-30T15:58:40Z",
      "updatedAt": "2026-07-01T18:39:28Z",
      "closedAt": "2026-07-01T18:39:28Z",
      "comments": [
        {
          "author": "emlun",
          "authorAssociation": "COLLABORATOR",
          "body": "On the one hand, this `context` is precisely the kind of additional parameter `COSE_Sign_Args` is defined for. We should therefore define a `COSE_Sign_Args` member for `context` when `alg: Ed25519ph`, and use this instead of ARKG in our `COSE_Sign_Args` examples.\n\nOn the other hand, we're defining Ed25519ph as a general COSE algorithm, and thus it can be used in other COSE cryptograms. There are no [COSE_Sign1 or COSE_Signature](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc9052/#name-signing-objects) headers defined for carrying a `context` value, so unless we want to define them we should probably define that `context` MUST be empty when using the Ed25519ph algorithm identifier in COSE_Sign1 and COSE_Signature structures.",
          "createdAt": "2026-06-30T16:09:42Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-06-30T16:09:42Z"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
